[Student "S"]
{South decides a limit raise is better than just jumping to game. North has heard enough and bids the slam. 

North is to play 6\S. East leads the \DQ.

Your first thought is probably that if you can guess the \CQ you will make all thirteen tricks.

So you win the \DK and play a \S to your \SK. When East discards a \D your second thought is probably that you <b>MUST</b> guess the \CQ just to make twelve tricks.

Hopefully your third thought is that if you use an elimination play you won't have to guess.

Play your \SA, leaving West with the master \SQ. Then eliminate \Ds by playing \DA and ruffing a \D in dummy.

Now eliminate \Hs by playing \HA, \HK, and ruffing a \H.

You are ready for the throw-in. Play a \S to West's \SQ.

[showcards N:ST,CK,CT,C2 S:S8,CA,CJ,C7]

West has just taken the defender's first trick. First and only. Because if he now plays a red card you will ruff in one hand and discard a losing \C from the other. And if he plays a \C you will no longer have a \C loser.

Most elimination plays work on the same principle. The biggest difference is usually the technique you have to use to complete the eliminations. 

Here it took two ruffs, one in each hand.}
[Play "W"]DQ

